  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Across Anthropology, published by Leuven University Press in 2020, has witnessed a modest citation count, indicating potential scholarly engagement. While currently lacking broader public discourse or social media attention, the work nonetheless seems to hold significance within the scholarly community.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite being published in 2020, Across Anthropology has not garnered citations, suggesting a limited immediate academic impact. However, it is important to recognize its ongoing potential for scholarly uptake as indicated by its existing citations. This provides a pathway for understanding its relevance in anthropological discussions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The book's commercial presence on platforms like Amazon and Goodreads suggests a degree of interest from the public and potential academic readers. This commercial linkage, although not a direct measure of academic impact, indicates that the content may be appealing to a broader audience, including those outside traditional academic circles.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Given the absence of online mentions and community discourse through platforms such as Wikipedia or Reddit, it appears that the book has yet to spark significant public debate or engagement. This may present an opportunity for future outreach efforts to raise awareness and discussion around its themes and content.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In conclusion, while there may be challenges currently related to visibility and citation, the presence of a commercial avenue suggests that Across Anthropology could gain traction in scholarly and public forums. Continued efforts to promote the book could enhance its recognition and foster a stronger academic footprint over time.</p>",
